Author’s Note: Some mature themes, but if you’re watching the show, then you’re old enough to read this. Oh, and the first chapter is more background for the story than anything else, not too much shippy goodness until later chapters.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
“Hey. You up for a run?” The man peered up at the young woman from his char in the hotel suite. He grinned and nodded.<br>
<br>
“I’m surprised you’re inviting me.” The woman rolled her eyes as she tied her dyed blonde hair back into a braid.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, well, I got enough crap from Dad and Bubba about ditching you last time.” She shot him a look. He stood up and shrugged. He was a large man. He was just a little over 6’7” and very athletically muscular. He flashed a knowing smile at her.<br>
<br>
“I’m your bodyguard Bunny, it would have been irresponsible for me not to tell your Dad that you weren’t being protected.” She shook her head and looked back at him through her gray-green eyes.<br>
<br>
“And what exactly are you protecting me from?” She started to stretch out. “Nothing and no one. You’ve been my bodyguard for how long now? Two years almost? And has anyone ever tried to attack me? No.” The man rolled his eyes and crossed his arms.<br>
<br>
“Seems like we’ve had this conversation before.”<br>
<br>
“And yet you never listen. Why is that?” He came over to her to help her stretch out a leg muscle.<br>
<br>
“Even if I quit, like the ones before me did, which I’m thinking had to do with you never obeying their orders for your own safety,” she glared at him. “Okay, even if I quit, you know your Dad is just going to replace me with someone else, just like he always does.” She let out a sigh and nodded.<br>
<br>
“I guess.” He gave her a reassuring grin and a pat on the shoulder.<br>
<br>
“So, indoor running track?” She got a hopeful, yet impish, smile on her face.<br>
<br>
“Foothills?” He glared at her, his previous grin faded.<br>
<br>
“No.” She frowned.<br>
<br>
“Come on, it’s completely safe.” His expression stayed the same, his arms crossed. “I won’t even try to ditch you this time,” she kidded and gave a toothy smile.<br>
<br>
“No.” She narrowed her eyes as she tried to think of a different approach, and then a grin crept across her lips ever so slightly.<br>
<br>
“Well, too bad Grr. We’re going to the foothills. Bubba wanted me to test the new AR prototype.” He furrowed his eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“He didn’t say anything to me about it.”<br>
<br>
“Well, last time I checked, you weren’t in research and development.” She smiled. He looked out the suite’s window and frowned.<br>
<br>
“Don’t you think you’ll get heatstroke or something? It’s still light out, and like a hundred and ten degrees.” She shrugged as she walked to the small refrigerator.<br>
<br>
“So I’ll bring water. You want one?” He closed his eyes for a moment in defeat.<br>
<br>
“Yeah.” She got the water bottles and practically bounced over to him.<br>
<br>
“Hold these, I need to put the prototype on.” She shoved the water bottles at him and went toward the bathroom. He shook his head. Bunny was a very attractive woman in her mid twenties. She wasn’t a traditional plastic surgery beauty; she had what most people referred to as ‘classic beauty’ with strong features. She was smart; one of the top designers at one of her Dad’s subsidiary companies. She had a good sense of humor, although it sometimes was a bit odd. She had a good figure; slim, athletic, but curvy. Around average height at 5’5”. Adrian could easily fall for her if she wasn’t such a pain, and if it wasn’t for her family, who was very protective of her. Her voice snapped him out of his thoughts and he swung around to face her. “Are you ready or what man?” He nodded and went over to the door to the hall where she was standing.<br>
<br>
“Sorry, I guess I just zoned for a second there.” She smiled.<br>
<br>
“Damn. I could have escaped,” she said half jokingly. “I’ll have to start paying more attention.” He rolled his eyes and opened the door for her.<br>
<br>
“You sure you don’t want to run on the indoor track? They’re supposed to have a good one here.” They walked toward the elevator.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, I’m sure. It probably smells like smoke too.” She made a disgusted face. “I don’t know what possessed Dad to have a convention here.” Adrian chuckled and they stepped onto the elevator.<br>
<br>
“I’m guessing something to do with the large convention facilities, and the fact that lots of people like to gamble in their personal time.” Bunny laughed.<br>
<br>
“Yeah? I’m guessing something to do with kickbacks. It’s kind of a creepy coincidence that he just happens to know every casino owner in Vegas, don’t you think?” He grinned.<br>
<br>
“Your father is a very wealthy and powerful man, I’m sure that he’s known the owners for some time.”<br>
<br>
“Uh-huh,” she said in a skeptical voice, as she turned around to look out the glass elevator. She scanned the area below and then focused in on something in a darkened corner. She squinted her eyes, trying to get a better look, and then her eyes widened in horror at what she saw. “Oh my God!” She screamed and Adrian rushed to her side to see what she was looking at, but he didn’t see it right away. She lifted a shaking hand to point at what she saw. A man standing over a body, the head separated and hanging from one hand, a butcher’s saw in the other. “Call the police,” she said in a quiet and worried voice.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
“Got another one Gris,” Brass said as Grissom and Sara walked up to him. He nodded and made his way over to the body. “Get those people out of here!” Brass yelled to a couple of officers, motioning to the press. This case was the fifth murder in under a month. The press dubbed the killer ‘The Headless Horseman’ because he took the heads of his victims with him. His victims all matched a profile too. Blonde (although it didn’t seem to matter whether it was natural) women in their mid to late twenties, all in good physical condition. No other links were found in their lives. The crime scenes were the worst though, and it was turning into a public relations nightmare. All of them were in very public places, with no evidence left behind except the body; but with no witnesses, at least until now. Brass was very pleased with this latest development, and knew Grissom would be too. He walked over to Grissom.<br>
<br>
“You get rid of the press?” Grissom asked, looking at Brass over his shoulder. Brass nodded.<br>
<br>
“For now.” Grissom turned his head around to face the body again. “Hey Grissom, there’s a witness this time.” This immediately caught both Grissom and Sara’s attention.<br>
<br>
“Who? Where?” Sara asked, excited at the possibility of a break in the case. Brass grinned.<br>
<br>
“Bunny Bouchard,” he said, motioning to her with his head. “As in only daughter of Clayton Bouchard.” Grissom and Sara swung their heads back around to look at him.<br>
<br>
“The billionaire Clayton Bouchard?” Grissom asked in an uneasy tone. Brass nodded.<br>
<br>
“The one and only. Apparently one of his companies is having some sort of convention here this weekend. Ms. Bouchard was on her way to go running in the foothills with her bodyguard,” he motioned toward the handsome athletic man standing near her, “when she saw the killer standing over the body from the glass elevator, head and saw in his hands.”<br>
<br>
Sara cringed. It was one thing to be exposed to that much blood and gore in her line of work, but to have to deal with it from Bunny’s point of view was an entirely different story. She expected that the daughter of one of the richest men in the world probably hadn’t had a lot of exposure to seeing killers or dead bodies. Grissom saw the hesitation on her face.<br>
<br>
“You want me to talk to her?” Sara looked over at him and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“No. I’ll do it.” She started to walk over to Bunny and noticed that her bodyguard stepped guardingly in front of her. She flashed a small smile and raised her identification badge. He frowned, but he stepped aside. “Ms. Bouchard?” Bunny looked over at Sara and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, can I help you?” Despite being obviously a little shaken, Sara noted that Bunny seemed to be handling everything all right, or at least was keeping that appearance. She gave her a grin.<br>
<br>
“Sara Sidle, crime scene investigation unit, can I ask you a couple of questions?” Bunny was staring at the body, but then turned her attention back to Sara.<br>
<br>
“Sure.”<br>
<br>
“I know you already told the police what happened, have they scheduled time with a sketch artist yet?” Bunny shrugged.<br>
<br>
“I’m not sure, they haven’t said anything.” Bunny looked over at Adrian, who placed a reassuring hand on her back.<br>
<br>
“It’s been a difficult last couple of hours, when can she go back to her room?” He asked. Sara gave a partial grin, but it didn’t reach the rest of her face. She thought that even for a bodyguard he was being a little possessive. Bunny shook her head.<br>
<br>
“No. I’m the one who told you to call the police. I’ll talk to them as long as they need me to,” Bunny stated firmly. He gave her a small glare, which Sara figured was not uncommon.<br>
<br>
“Your Dad’s not going to like you being out here like this. You want me to call him?” It definitely sounded like a threat of some kind. Bunny sighed.<br>
<br>
“Well, he’s going to find out about this sooner or later,” she motioned with her hands at the crime scene. “It’s not really something I can hide now is it?” Her voice had a tinge of anger, but mostly despair. He sighed and bowed his head slightly, and then raised his eyes a little to look at her face. He could see the tears starting to well up in her eyes.<br>
<br>
“It’s my fault, I shouldn’t have let you talk me into going to the foothills to run.” He sighed again, running his hand through his short, dark hair. Adrian shook his head. “Your step brother and that damn prototype,” he mumbled. Bunny’s eyes flew wide open in response to what he said. How could she have forgotten?<br>
<br>
“Oh my God! The AR prototype! I completely forgot!” She turned excitedly toward Sara who was watching her with mild confusion. “What kind of operating system does your lab have?” She rushed the words out. Sara furrowed her brow. “You know, what type, model, make, year it was put out, software, anything?”<br>
<br>
“Why?” Sara asked. Grissom came over to the three people when he heard Bunny get so excited.<br>
<br>
“Something wrong?” He asked in his calmest voice possible.<br>
<br>
“The AR prototype. If it worked then you should be able to have a digital shot of the killer on the lens,” Bunny explained. Grissom and Sara exchanged looks.<br>
<br>
“You took pictures of the killer?” Grissom asked to clarify. Bunny shook her head.<br>
<br>
“No, no, no. The … geez. This is going to take way too long to explain, I’ll just have to show you. Is your lab’s operating system compatible with the 12 GP modulator?” Grissom raised his eyebrows. For someone he presumed was just a rich man’s daughter, she seemed to have a lot of knowledge about computers. He shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I wish. Our budget isn’t quite that large.” Bunny frowned, but it changed to an excited smile when she saw an angry handsome man arguing with Brass. She waved to him.<br>
<br>
“Ford! Over here!” His face turned in her direction and he walked away from Brass. When he got to her, he embraced her in a large hug. A possessive hug. Grissom and Sara both raised an eyebrow when they looked at each other. Grissom mouthed ‘boyfriend?’. Sara shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Bunny! Thank God! Are you alright?” He pulled away, but kept his hands on her arms.<br>
<br>
“Of course, I’m not the one who was killed,” Bunny shot back in a semi sarcastic manner. She looked at Grissom and Sara. “Oh, sorry. I’m really bad about introductions. This is my step brother Ford Abernathy.” Ford extended a hand to shake each of theirs. She turned back to Ford. “I need a converter for their system to make it compatible with the 12 GP modulator,” she stated. She struck Grissom as a woman who was very used to getting her own way.<br>
<br>
“Why?”<br>
<br>
“Uh…” she paused and looked at Adrian who was arching an eyebrow at her. She sighed and slumped her shoulders a little. “I was testing out my new AR prototype. I was going to take it for a run in the foothills, but then, well, you know.” Ford narrowed his blue eyes at her.<br>
<br>
“You were going running in the foothills?” Ford asked angrily. “What the hell were you thinking? You know Adrian wouldn’t be able to properly protect you by himself in an area that large.”<br>
<br>
“I just wanted to get outside Bubba.” His anger melted a little when she used his nickname. “I hate being trapped inside all the time. It’s boring.” He pulled her into a hug again.<br>
<br>
“I know.” He rubbed her back with one hand. “We just want you to be safe you know. We’re not trying to be mean.” She rolled her eyes and pulled away.<br>
<br>
“I guess.” Grissom was getting a strange vibe from Ford and pursed his lips in thought.<br>
<br>
“Well, look on the bright side,” he interjected. “Now we finally have a witness.”<br>
<br>
