<br>
“What the …?” Grissom just raised his eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“I guess when the president of the company says to jump, you don’t ask questions,” he reasoned. Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“I thought they were only going to send over a converter or something,” she shook her head in confusion. Grissom shrugged.<br>
<br>
“I talked to Ford a little when you were with Brass. He said it would be better if we just had a new system, that way we would get the best results.” Greg came bounding out of the lab, his face showing his obvious delight in the situation.<br>
<br>
“When did we get the budget for the entire state?” He joked, his smile practically plastered to his face. Grissom just eyed him.<br>
<br>
“We didn’t. It’s a gift,” Grissom explained. Greg’s eyes grew wide in surprise.<br>
<br>
“A gift? You’re joking right? I’ve only opened one package and…” Grissom furrowed his eyebrows, and picked up one of the delivery slips.<br>
<br>
“I don’t think any of these were addressed to you were they Greg?” Grissom’s statement didn’t faze Greg at all. He just stared at him.<br>
<br>
“It’s from Abernathy Systems Grissom,” he said, explaining to Grissom like he was a child. Grissom cocked an eyebrow and crossed his arms. “Abernathy Systems! Hello! You know how many government contracts those guys have?” He directed his attention toward Sara. It was easier to not have to look at Grissom’s apparent displeasure while he was talking. “And, I’m not just talking military here, think CIA, NSA, and all those other agencies they don’t even admit exist.” Greg clearly looked impressed and Grissom had to hold back a chuckle, though a half grin did find it’s way to his face.<br>
<br>
“I know Greg. It’s a new computer system and related lab equipment.” Greg nodded.<br>
<br>
“I figured it was something like that since what I opened,” he paused and shook his head. “It’s so new I’ve never even read about it.” Grissom and Sara shared a look, wondering what they had gotten themselves into.<br>
<br>
Nick and Warrick walked in to the building, oblivious to the situation in front of them.<br>
<br>
“Hey guys!” Nick greeted with a smile. His demeanor quickly changed to surprise and confusion, as did Warrick’s, when they saw the boxes taking up so much room. “Uh, what’s going on?” Greg got a proud and cocky look on his face, as if he was responsible.<br>
<br>
“New system,” he gloated, standing up straight, he raised his eyebrows once and smiled broadly. Warrick arched an eyebrow at Grissom, who just shook his head slightly.<br>
<br>
“Everybody to my office, I’ll explain there.” Warrick nodded and began to follow, until he read the side of one of the boxes.<br>
<br>
“Abernathy Systems?! Whoa!” He exclaimed, clearly impressed. Grissom sighed and turned around for a moment.<br>
<br>
“My office.” Warrick gave a nod of his head.<br>
<br>
“Right.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara and Nick sat down on the two chairs on the other side of Grissom’s desk. Grissom sat down in his. Warrick and Greg stood behind Sara and Nick.<br>
<br>
“So what’s with the boxes Gris?” Nick asked. Grissom gave a half grin.<br>
<br>
“We have a witness in ‘The Headless Horseman’,” he said the name with disdain. He hated when the press assigned nicknames to the killers. It only spurred them on. “Case. A woman saw him from a nearby glass elevator.” Nick, Warrick, and Greg were all pleasantly surprised.<br>
<br>
“That’s great,” Nick said. “Did she get a good look at him?” Sara turned to answer him.<br>
<br>
“That’s where the new system comes in,” she said. He furrowed his eyebrows a little. “Her step brother is Ford Abernathy. Apparently…” Greg cut her off.<br>
<br>
“Ford Abernathy? The president of Abernathy Systems?” Grissom nodded. “That would mean the witness is Bunny Bouchard,” he thought out loud. Grissom looked a little puzzled. Warrick clearly got the implication that Greg was giving.<br>
<br>
“Yes,” Grissom answered. Greg nervously ran his hand over his head.<br>
<br>
“And yet you’re sitting here like this is nothing. Why?” Greg asked. Grissom got a somewhat bemused expression on his face.<br>
<br>
“I know she’s Clayton Bouchard’s daughter Greg, but I never saw you as someone who follows the social pages.” Warrick chuckled.<br>
<br>
“That’s not why he’s impressed Gris.” Grissom leaned back in his chair, giving a look to Warrick that was permission to go on. “She’s one of the top technical designers there is. You know like on James Bond? The guy that makes all those cool little toys? That’s her. Only for real.” Greg nodded in agreement.<br>
<br>
“W-well,” Greg turned to Warrick, “except she works for a private company instead of for the government directly.” Warrick rolled his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Same thing.”<br>
<br>
“Ah,” Grissom said, digesting the information. “She said something about testing an AR prototype, she said if it worked then there should be a picture of our killer on it.” Sara smiled and faced the others.<br>
<br>
“Except the prototype wasn’t going to work with our system.”<br>
<br>
“So her step brother donated the equipment necessary to use it,” Nick finished, guessing where Sara was going.<br>
<br>
“Yep,” Sara said, smiling at Nick.<br>
<br>
“He donated all of this equipment just so it would be compatible with a prototype that may or may not even work?” Greg asked in astonishment. Grissom frowned, thinking back to the strange vibe he got from Ford.<br>
<br>
“He seemed to be pretty protective of her,” Grissom answered. “Maybe he just wants to get this guy off the streets as much as we do.” Nick snorted.<br>
<br>
“Or maybe he just doesn’t want his top designer to be killed,” he said in a semi sarcastic tone. Grissom’s frown hadn’t faded. Sara shook her head a little.<br>
<br>
“That could be part of it, but I think he really cares for her. Do we know how long they’ve been step siblings?” Sara directed the question to Grissom, but Greg answered.<br>
<br>
“Seven years.” Everyone turned to look at him. “What? It’s public knowledge, and it was a big news item at the time.” Grissom’s mouth was hanging a little bit open, but he closed it and nodded.<br>
<br>
“That could certainly be long enough for them to have developed actual sibling feelings for each other, rather than just regarding the other as a step,” Sara theorized. Grissom looked down. He didn’t get the impression that Ford’s feelings were brotherly; he acted more like an obsessive boyfriend. He shook his head. Maybe he misread the situation. Wouldn’t he have been that concerned if one of his team had been in that position? He decided to change the topic, aware that he had been keeping his thoughts to himself long enough for everyone to be staring expectantly at him. He took off his glasses for a moment and rubbed his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Ms. Bouchard is going to be coming in with the prototype as soon as we call her to let her know that the new system is set up.” Greg and Warrick were suddenly more interested in the conversation.<br>
<br>
“Really?” Greg asked. “She’s coming here? She’s not just sending some lackey?” He started pacing around nervously in a little circle and mumbling to himself. “Oh man, this is so big. I can’t believe she’s actually coming to my lab.” Grissom cocked an eyebrow at him and got up from his seat.<br>
<br>
“Yes, she’s actually coming here. I got the impression that the prototype is kind of complicated.” He stepped closer to Greg, who was now near the door. “And when did it become your lab?” Greg looked up at him and gave a little grin. Grissom rolled his eyes. “We should get this stuff set up, call in some of Ecklie’s crew if you need help. I have the feeling she’s not going to want to stay cooped up in that hotel room for long.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
It took them a full three hours to remove the old equipment and install the new equipment, but they still hadn’t figured out how to install the new software or transfer any of the old files. They were all getting frustrated. What had seemed like a wonderful gift was turning into a big problem very quickly, as they still had other cases to work on. Grissom’s cell phone rang.<br>
<br>
“Grissom.” It was the front desk.<br>
<br>
“Sir, there’s a Clayton Bouchard here to see you.” Her voice became a little hushed, as if she was trying to make it so the man couldn’t hear her as well. “He looks pretty important, couple of bodyguards and the whole bit.” Grissom sighed. A headache was starting to build from the stress of the situation.<br>
<br>
“Tell him I’m on my way out to meet him.” The others turned to him at his statement and he clicked his phone off. “Mr. Bouchard is here so I’m going to speak with him.” He got to the door and then turned around and pointed at them. “Behave yourselves.” Sara and Nick smiled, despite the intense conditions they were working under. This gesture didn’t go unnoticed by Grissom. He had been watching their behavior toward each other turn from hostile at the very beginning to what now seemed to be a brother/sister relationship. He never considered the possibility it could be anything more than that, but now, thinking about how Ford Abernathy had been acting toward his actual stepsister, he wasn’t as sure. He frowned. Nick and Sara weren’t related at all. Not by blood or just marriage. It gave him a queasy feeling that he forced himself to shove down when he saw the man standing in the lobby.<br>
<br>
Clayton Bouchard. The quintessential billionaire. Tall, still in good shape for his age, good looking, and the aura of power that seemed to radiate from him. Grissom sighed. Bouchard was talking with Brass, and Brass noticed him first and waved him over.<br>
<br>
“Grissom, I’d like you meet Mr. Bouchard, Mr. Bouchard, this is Gil Grissom, our director of forensics.” They extended their arms to shake the other’s hand. “He’s Bunny Bouchard’s father.” Grissom nodded.<br>
<br>
“Nice to meet you sir.” Grissom cringed inwardly at the respect this man commanded. He always tried to be respectful, it was a good way to hide what Catherine referred to as his ‘lack of social skills’, but he rarely called anyone sir or ma’m. He was used to putting himself in the authority position, especially with anyone involved with a case. Bouchard nodded and then frowned.<br>
<br>
“Are you feeling alright Mr. Grissom?” Grissom got a confused look on his face. “Sorry, I didn’t mean to offend you, you just look kind of pale, like you’re going to be sick.” Grissom gave a half grin. Bouchard was observant. He should have expected that. People didn’t get to his position of wealth and power by letting things slip by them.<br>
<br>
“Trying to fight off an oncoming headache,” Grissom explained. Bouchard smiled and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Migraine? Ford gets those, has to sleep them off because none of the medicines work for him.” Grissom noticed how friendly and outgoing Bouchard was. He imagined that Bunny was also that way under normal circumstances, but then, he hadn’t seen her under normal circumstances. Grissom shook his head a little.<br>
<br>
“It’s not a migraine,” he paused, “not yet anyway.”<br>
<br>
“So, we can use my office to talk if you’d like,” Brass offered. Bouchard shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I don’t think that will be necessary. I just wanted to make sure that my daughter isn’t going to be in any sort of danger.” Grissom frowned.<br>
<br>
“I can’t guarantee that sir. I have no way of knowing whether the killer saw her as well,” Grissom said honestly. Bouchard’s concern crossed his features.<br>
<br>
“Would it be safer if I had her sent home?” Grissom considered Bouchard’s question, the wording more than the meaning behind it. Sent home. Maybe he had been overreacting to Ford’s concern for her. It seemed that everyone around her treated her like she was an object to be protected at all costs, except her bodyguard, interestingly enough, who seemed to be more concerned about her as a person.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know if she would go Mr. Bouchard,” Grissom paused, watching the man roll his eyes slightly. “She said something about a prototype that might be able to help us, she seemed pretty intent on being the one to set it up.” Bouchard sighed and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, I figured. She’s stubborn and fearless,” he said, a tinge of pride ringing in his voice. Grissom grinned, and then he saw Ford, Bunny, Adrian, and a man he presumed was Ford’s bodyguard, come in through the doors. Bouchard followed Grissom’s eyes and smiled at the site. “Hey sweetheart,” he said, reaching out his arms for a hug from his daughter. She smiled and came over to give him a hug. Ford turned to Grissom.<br>
<br>
“You have the new system in place?” Grissom dropped his head.<br>
<br>
“We’re having trouble setting up the new software and transferring files,” he admitted. Ford smiled a big smile, revealing small dimples in his cheeks.<br>
<br>
“No problem. Lead the way and I’ll get it taken care of in a few minutes.” Grissom gave him a look. He had struck him as intelligent when he first met him, but more in a leadership and business capacity rather than in a technological sense. But, he had nothing to lose, and they were going to need every minute they could get. The killer was speeding up his schedule.<br>
