<br>
“How did you do that so fast? We were trying to get it hooked up for over an hour,” Sara said in an exasperated voice. Ford stood up and faced her, giving her a friendly, but not flirtatious, smile. Sara blushed a little before he even said anything. ‘Whoever said they couldn’t make a living with just a smile never met this guy,’ she silently thought.<br>
<br>
“It’s no big deal,” he said calmly, and then smiled again. “Of course, I work with these systems every day, so I’m used to it.” Grissom frowned, but Ford was still directing his attention toward Sara. He made a mental note to ask Greg if he knew any more about this guy. Handsome, smart, and charming could be a dangerous combination, especially with the added element of wealth. Ford turned to face Grissom. “Mr. Grissom.” Grissom was startled out of his train of thought.<br>
<br>
“Yes?” Ford grinned as he saw the expression on Grissom’s face and heard the tone in his voice. His blue eyes quickly flashed between Grissom and Sara and back again. Grissom was apparently the only one who noticed. ‘Oh great, he’s perceptive too.’<br>
<br>
“Could you tell Bunny to come in here now? It’s all ready.” Grissom nodded.<br>
<br>
“So what does this prototype do exactly?” Warrick asked as Grissom left the room. Ford shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Got me. The AR prototype was originally started as an artificial retina design to help blind people see images by sending electric pulses and regenerating some nerves, but there’s no telling what it does now.” Ford chuckled. Nick furrowed his brows.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?” Ford crossed his arms and shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Bunny has a habit of getting sidetracked,” he explained without giving anything away.<br>
<br>
“Well, as long as it helps us catch this guy,” Sara said. Ford nodded.<br>
<br>
“I want to see him caught as much as you all do,” Ford said. “If for no other reason than the fact that he scared Bun. There’s barely anything that scares her. This guy must be a monster.” Grissom walked in with Bunny and Adrian. “Where’s your Dad?” Bunny grinned, obviously more at ease than earlier that day.<br>
<br>
“Work beckoned,” she stated in a non-chalant tone, indicating that it didn’t bother her. Grissom grinned to himself. ‘Of course it didn’t bother her, she doesn’t like being hovered over.’ “So we’re all set?” Ford nodded and walked over to her, putting his hand on the small of her back.<br>
<br>
“They were asking me what this little AR prototype of yours does,” Ford said, his mouth close enough to her that Grissom could see a few strands of her hair move when he spoke. She didn’t look at, or answer him, but remained focused on a small case she was taking out of her purse. “Bunny?” Her eyes darted up to him quickly, and then back down as she popped the lock on the case open.<br>
<br>
“Where is the 12 GP modulator?” She asked, looking around. Ford pointed to it and she moved away from him and over to it, but he followed close behind. Greg got a look at what was in the case.<br>
<br>
“Contacts?” He asked, surprised. She took the contacts out and placed them on a special grid inside the modulator, then closed the consul.<br>
<br>
“Not exactly,” she responded, sitting down at the computer. She typed a few things in to begin the program. “Did you send them a voice recognition program or do I need to do this the old fashioned way?” She directed the question to Ford, who was standing directly behind her. He gave a mock frown.<br>
<br>
“It’s in there. Lazy,” he kidded. She smiled.<br>
<br>
“So?” Bunny wasn’t upset by Ford’s accusation. She had gotten used to their banter as if it was completely normal. Grissom noticed Adrian standing by the door, looking out every once and again, and glaring at Ford any time he glanced at Bunny. He gave him a nod in recognition. “Ha! Here we go,” Bunny said excitedly. An image appeared up on a large viewing screen near the wall.<br>
<br>
“A digital movie?” Grissom asked in surprise. Bunny moved her head back and forth in a bouncy manner.<br>
<br>
“No, well, sort of. The prototype records the images that the person wearing it sees, and yes, kind of in a movie like format. No sounds though, and I need to enhance the zoom and low light capabilities.” Sara looked at her in shock.<br>
<br>
“That’s not possible,” she shook her head. Bunny grinned.<br>
<br>
“Of course it is,” she responded, not taking her eyes off the screen. “Computer recognition please.” The computer beeped. “Skip forward five minutes.” The image on screen leapt ahead to the killer running away and disappearing into the shadows. “Hmm. Too far. Skip backward three minutes.” The image went back to when she was first looking out the glass elevator. Bunny’s eyes were focused on the part of the screen she knew she would see the man in. Sara caught on to that and was looking there too. She gasped at what she saw next. The killer was finishing the removal of the head, and then he stood up with the saw and the head in his hands. “Freeze image. Zoom in on the bottom right hand corner, coordinates B-50.” Everyone in the room had their eyes glued to the screen in disbelief. “Digitally enhance and enlarge image.” In front of them was a clear picture of the man who had been so elusive. He never left any evidence at the scenes other than the body, and there had never been any witnesses until now. Adrian furrowed his brow.<br>
<br>
“This image is from your point of view right?” Bunny nodded. Adrian quickly became concerned again and took his cell phone out.<br>
<br>
“Who are you calling?” She asked.<br>
<br>
“Your father. You need extra security and you need to get out of Las Vegas right away.” Bunny shot him a questioning and confused expression.<br>
<br>
“Why?” Adrian pointed at the screen, to the man’s face.<br>
<br>
“He’s looking directly at you.” Grissom cringed and Sara’s mouth dropped open. Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“He’s right.”<br>
<br>
“So?” Bunny asked, apparently not seeing why this was a big deal. Grissom sighed before answering.<br>
<br>
“You fit the victim profile. Blonde, in good shape physically.” Ford’s eyes grew large and panicked.<br>
<br>
“What?!” He questioned, half panicked, half angered. Nick and Warrick exchanged ‘oh, crap’ looks at each other. Adrian was talking to Bouchard on the phone throughout the conversation, but he caught the part before Ford flipped out. He came over to Bunny and grabbed her arm forcefully, but not cruelly, and started to lead her to the door.<br>
<br>
“We need to get you out of here now. Additional security will be waiting at the hotel to help escort you to your Dad’s plane at the airport.” Bunny pulled her arm away from him.<br>
<br>
“Geez, will you calm down? It’s not like it’s a big deal. He doesn’t know who I am, and there are a few thousand women here who fit that profile.” Both Ford and Adrian gave her warning looks, which she ignored. “Besides, they have a picture of him now. They can run it through a facial recognition database and see if they get a match, and in the meantime they can send the police out with the picture in hand.” Sara was impressed by Bunny’s bravery, or foolishness, she hadn’t quite figured out which it was yet. She theorized that this was more like Bunny’s day to day personality, strong and stubborn, but lighthearted. She didn’t want her to get hurt though, and even with a bodyguard as frightening as Adrian, she could still be taken by the killer. Ford, still standing next to Bunny wrapped his arm around her waist. In an almost whispered voice, he spoke to her.<br>
<br>
“Have you taken into consideration that this could very well be the man who was stalking you a year ago? We never did find out who it was or what he looked like.” Bunny rolled her eyes. Nick was the only one close enough to catch the comment and he closed his eyes, pushing down his emotions about his own brush with a stalker.<br>
<br>
“How long were you stalked?” Nick asked in a concerned tone. She looked over at him, her expression unreadable. She sighed.<br>
<br>
“Only a couple of months. It wasn’t as bad as a lot of people get. He just sent flowers and notes of his undying affection every day. More like a secret admirer,” she said, although there was a quality to her voice that suggested that it wasn’t like that all. Adrian and Ford both scoffed.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, a secret admirer who writes notes with blood is called a stalker Bunny.” Ford said. Sara’s eyes widened in disgust and horror, but also in query.<br>
<br>
“Did you ever have the blood analyzed?” Sara asked. Maybe it wasn’t an appropriate question given the circumstances, but she wouldn’t know unless she asked. Grissom grinned at her, as he had been ready to ask the same question until she interjected. Ford nodded, now rubbing his hand up and down Bunny’s upper arm.<br>
<br>
“Every single note. They all were from different people, all female if I remember correctly. The police suggested that he might be a worker at a bloodbank or hospital or something, somewhere he could have ready access to a supply of blood.” Grissom nodded. That sounded reasonable, but there was still something nagging at the back of his head.<br>
<br>
“Do you still have the results?” He asked. Ford was taken aback by the question and looked surprised.<br>
<br>
“I have no idea. Why?” Grissom looked down, trying to figure out a way to phrase the answer delicately.<br>
<br>
“If they were all female samples, and although this is a big leap, if it is the same man who was stalking her…” Ford’s face paled, receiving Grissom’s unspoken implication.<br>
<br>
“Then he could have been killed those women too,” he said in a hushed and disbelieving voice. “Oh, God.” Bunny arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“That’s quite a leap isn’t it? I mean, people are stalked every day and it’s not all by the same person.” Her question, although the wording of it suggested that she thought Grissom’s theory was crap, was in the tone of someone who recognized that it could be a possibility and didn’t want to believe it. Ford ignored her statement and turned to Adrian.<br>
<br>
“Have the extra security meet us over here instead, and I’m going to call her Dad’s office and see if they still have the results on file.” He turned to Grissom. “Do you have access to the federal DNA databank?” Grissom’s eyes grew large and he cocked an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“They’re keeping DNA on file?” Ford gave a half grin and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Makes it easier to compare results to previous convictions and such I imagine. Do you want me to have them run the note results through that first?” Grissom nodded and Ford followed suit. “Give me your office fax number and I’ll have them send the results over as soon as they’re done running them.” He turned to Bunny and spoke to her in a very authoritative tone. “You. You don’t leave without Adrian and the other security that’s coming. You don’t go to a different room in this building unless you have other people with you. You don’t ditch them. Understand?” Bunny gave a mischievous grin. “I mean it.” She rolled her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Fine Bubba, I understand.” He pulled her into a hug and kissed her forehead, then left the room. “Stupid Vegas, didn’t even want to come here in the first place,” she mumbled. Nick walked over to her.<br>
<br>
“We can go to the break room if you’d like,” he drawled. “You’ll probably be more comfortable there, and I know there’s still a lot of work that needs to be done on other cases.” He looked at Grissom for unspoken permission and he nodded. “Come on, I’ll show you the way.” Adrian walked with them while he finished his phone call.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Bunny sat down in one of the break room chairs, stretching her feet out so they were lying on top of a parallel one.<br>
<br>
“Make yourself comfortable,” Adrian joked. Bunny smiled, but it didn’t reach her eyes. Nick sat down across from her, opening a Coke.<br>
<br>
“You want one?” Bunny arched an eyebrow and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“Eeww, no. You know how bad that is for you?” Nick smiled.<br>
<br>
“Health nut huh?” She shot him a glare, but it wasn’t malicious.<br>
<br>
“Not really, but drinking out of aluminum cans contributes to heavy metals toxicity, and I don’t really care to have Alzheimer’s when I get older,” Bunny retorted. Nick’s mouth was slightly agape. Adrian snorted.<br>
<br>
“And I’m sure working in a lab with those sorts of materials doesn’t do anything to you right?” She grinned.<br>
<br>
“Well, I’m not swallowing them there.” There was a little chuckle that filled the room, and then a silent pause. Nick looked thoughtful.<br>
<br>
“So is your brother always like that?” Adrian eyed him. He knew what he was talking about, but to bring up the subject with Bunny was a bit dangerous.<br>
<br>
“Is he always like what?” Bunny asked somewhat innocently. “Like an overprotective jackass? Yes.” Nick snorted and some of the pop that was in his mouth flew out. He quickly grabbed a couple of paper towels to clean up the mess.<br>
<br>
“Uh, well, that too.” He paused. He knew one of the main reasons he had been hired was because of his interpersonal skills, but some subjects were delicate, especially if the person you were speaking with didn’t know what you were talking about. “He just seems awfully fond of you is all.” Adrian winced a little, and then turned to look out in the hallway again so Bunny wouldn’t be able to see the look on his face. Bunny gave Nick a confused look and shrugged.<br>
<br>
“We’re pretty good friends for being step siblings if that’s what you mean.” Nick gave a half grin. Maybe it would be better if he didn’t continue right now; she probably had a lot of other things on her mind. And another was about to come.<br>
<br>
Warrick ran into the break room and almost got knocked over by Adrian, who was blocking the entryway. He looked at Nick.<br>
<br>
“There’s been another one,” he said, distressed at the situation, but still trying to maintain his cool exterior. “Grissom said for you and I to take this one.” Nick got up from his chair and threw his Coke can into the recycling bin. He turned around to face Bunny.<br>
<br>
“Are you going to be okay here?” Bunny snorted.<br>
<br>
“I’m in a police building with my bodyguard. I’m fairly certain I’ll survive,” she said sarcastically and waved him away. Adrian chuckled. Nick nodded and he and Warrick left to go to the latest ‘headless horseman’ crime scene.<br>
