<br>
“They haven’t been cleared out yet?” Brass sighed.<br>
<br>
“No, and thanks to our beloved Sheriff, they’re going to be staying a little while longer. He decided to issue a statement, but he hasn’t showed up yet.” Warrick shook his head and put his gloves on.<br>
<br>
“Doesn’t he know that serial killers get off on the attention?” Brass rolled his eyes.<br>
<br>
“So does he.” Nick snorted and then pointed to the woman’s body.<br>
<br>
“Any I.D. on her?” Brass nodded.<br>
<br>
“Yeah. This guy’s definitely not in it for the money. She had over two grand in her purse that she won in the casino.” Nick whistled as he snapped his gloves on. Brass looked at his notepad. “Jaimie Uller, visiting from South Dakota. We talked to the guy at the door and he said the woman on the I.D. was wearing those clothes.” Nick nodded, walking over to the woman, ignoring the questions the members of the press were calling out. Warrick furrowed his brow.<br>
<br>
“Guy at the door? He didn’t see the murder though?” Brass frowned.<br>
<br>
“Not in his direct line of vision for greeting people. And, before you ask, I had the security cameras checked out too, all snow for the outside cameras on that side.”<br>
<br>
“And no other witnesses?” Nick asked as he fingerprinted the lifeless hands.<br>
<br>
“As usual,” Brass quipped.<br>
<br>
“How does this guy keep getting away with this in such crowded areas? I could understand if he was killing them out in the middle of nowhere, but look around.” The three briefly took in the area with their eyes. “Even without the press here, there are at least a thousand people on this street.” Warrick nodded in agreement.<br>
<br>
“At least we have a picture of him now.” Brass raised an eyebrow in surprise.<br>
<br>
“Since when?” Nick stood up and grinned at Brass, while Warrick looked for any other evidence at the scene.<br>
<br>
“Your last witness, Bunny Bouchard, is a big technology designer. She got a pic of the guy off her contact lens.”<br>
<br>
“Got it with you?” Warrick nodded his head from his crouching position.<br>
<br>
“In the car.” Brass smiled.<br>
<br>
“Keys?” Nick tossed the keys at Brass. “Just in time for Mobley’s speech,” he motioned toward the Sheriff, who was just arriving.<br>
<br>
Warrick, paying attention to Brass only as background noise, narrowed his eyes at something on the body. He lifted her tank top just enough to see a card that had been shoved under it.<br>
<br>
“Nick!” Nick came over and Warrick held up the small card, the kind that usually comes with flowers. It was sealed. On the front, it had a stamp of a rabbit on it.<br>
<br>
“@#%$,” Nick mumbled. “Ever wish Grissom was sometimes wrong about these things?” Warrick frowned as he placed the card into an evidence bag.<br>
<br>
“Yeah.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Adrian stood in the doorway of the break room staring at Bunny, who was just sitting there flipping through the TV channels with the remote. She turned it off.<br>
<br>
“This is so-oo boring,” she whined, flopping her face on top of her crossed arms on the table. He flashed her a smile when she looked up at him. “You think is funny don’t you?” He chuckled.<br>
<br>
“I just find it interesting that you’re stuck here because you wouldn’t listen to me about not going running in the foothills.” She rolled her eyes and rested a check against her palm.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, instead I could have been stuck in my hotel room. Big difference,” she said sarcastically. She didn’t like being told what to do or being caged, both of which were getting on her nerves and making her snippy. Adrian arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Well, there’s more you can do in your hotel room,” he said semi- suggestively. He would never cross that line unless she was the one to initiate, but a little flirting might help cheer her up. She laughed.<br>
<br>
“Yeah right,” she said, not getting the hint that he was talking about himself. “When’s the last time I actually had a date? Dad tried to set me up with that son of I don’t even remember who a little over a year ago, but Ford nixed that before I could even meet the guy.” Adrian frowned. Her social life wasn’t like that of typical women of her station. She was beautiful, and could certainly get any guy she set her mind to getting, but her Dad or Ford usually got in the way, saying they wouldn’t be good enough for her. And, rather than get into a big fight, she would usually give in. Most men, from Adrian’s vantage point, didn’t seem to be smart or good looking enough, or a combination of the two, to even warrant a second look from her, and he figured that was why she didn’t fight with them about it like she did for everything else.<br>
<br>
“Have you talked to Ford about that?” He asked, taking a step closer to her. Bunny shrugged, and then stood up to stretch.<br>
<br>
“It’s not that big of a deal. I’m sure if I actually find a guy that I’m interested in then he’ll back off.” Adrian frowned. “What?”<br>
<br>
“Don’t count on it.” Bunny furrowed her brow at him.<br>
<br>
“Why not?” Adrian sighed, trying to think of a tactful way to say what needed to be said.<br>
<br>
“Well, Ford is…” Ford walked into the doorway.<br>
<br>
“Ford is what?” He asked cocking an eyebrow. Adrian turned his head around.<br>
<br>
“Extra security here?” Adrian asked, bypassing Ford’s question. Ford nodded.<br>
<br>
“They’re here,” he said, then turning his attention to Bunny. “But you’re not going to like it.” She scowled at him.<br>
<br>
“I already don’t like it.” Ford smiled and walked over to her.<br>
<br>
“Well, then you’re not going to like it even more. It seems that the local sheriff just held a press conference.” Bunny frowned. “Exactly,” Ford said, as if reading her thoughts. “Which means that your Dad has about five extra guys out there.”<br>
<br>
“Crap. When did you find this out? Nobody told us and we’ve been here the whole time.” Ford placed a reassuring hand on her back.<br>
<br>
“It was on TV, they just had a press conference. You could probably catch a recap if you want to turn it on,” he said, pointing at the TV. Bunny sighed and leaned her head against Ford’s chest. He wrapped his arms around her and kissed the top of her head. “Don’t worry, it’s going to be okay.” Adrian winced at Ford’s affection toward Bunny. She obviously only viewed it as brotherly love, and just as obvious was how Ford seemed to take advantage of that fact. She pulled away from him.<br>
<br>
“So what’s going to happen now?” Ford shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Adrian will have to coordinate with them, and then we’ll leave Las Vegas and go somewhere safe.” Ford gave her a half grin. Bunny sighed.<br>
<br>
“This is completely unnecessary.”<br>
<br>
“Better to be safe than sorry.”<br>
<br>
“I guess.” Bunny nodded and walked over to Adrian, who was now standing in the doorway again, looking out into the hallway.<br>
<br>
“I don’t suppose I could give you a bribe to just let me accidentally get away?” She asked with a smile in a somewhat lowered voice, already knowing what the answer would be. Adrian chuckled.<br>
<br>
“No.” She let her smile drop momentarily, but quickly returned it.<br>
<br>
“Are you sure? I could make it worth your while,” she said half jokingly, rubbing her thumb against her finger. Adrian and Ford both laughed.<br>
<br>
“Do you really think your Dad would have hired him as your bodyguard if he thought for a second that you would be able to bribe him?” Ford asked.<br>
<br>
“And do you really think that I would actually just let you go when there’s a serial killer on the loose who’s seen your face, and who’s victim profile you match?” Adrian added. Bunny sighed and went back over to stand next to Ford.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Nick and Warrick came back to the lab to drop off the evidence for processing, and to tell Grissom about what they found at the scene. They had seen the five men, that they presumed were there for Bunny’s extra security, in the lobby. Nick shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I kind of feel sorry for her,” he said. Warrick raised an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, poor little rich girl syndrome. That’s gotta suck,” he replied, deadpan. “Her Dad must have seen the press conference. I doubt there’d be so many guys here otherwise.” Nick frowned.<br>
<br>
“Don’t be so sure.” They reached the lab door. “Hey guys, guess what we found.” Nick held up the evidence bag. Grissom furrowed his brow, as if trying to see the card from his location across the room. Sara, however, approached them quickly, and swiftly snapped the bag away from Nick’s fingers. “Since when is this your case?” Nick asked in a mock defensive tone. Sara smiled.<br>
<br>
“Since I said so.” Grissom frowned as he watched Sara banter back and forth with Nick. She held the bag open as she reached in with her glove- covered hands. “A card?” Nick smiled and turned it over so she could see the rabbit stamp on the other side. “Oh crap.” She looked up, searching the room for Grissom, who had moved closer to her as if feeling his territory was threatened. He saw the concern and panic in her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Sara?” The question went unanswered as an unseen knockout gas filtered through the ventilation system. Sara, because of her weight, was the first one to drop. Greg was next, and the others followed quickly. The guards in the security monitor room didn’t have a chance to see all of their screens go to static.<br>
<br>
A tall man wearing a gas mask came into the building, looking at the people lying on the floor. The stomping sound from his combat boots reverberated through the halls, but no one was awake to hear it. He headed down the corridor, already knowing his destination. He stopped at the break room door and a grin crossed his lips when he saw Bunny lying unconscious. The grin quickly turned to a frown when he saw Ford next to her. He walked over to where Ford lay, the anger seething through his motions.<br>
<br>
“She and I belong together!” He yelled at the unconscious man. “How dare you try to keep her away from me!” He pulled his foot back and kicked Ford hard in the head. Blood came immediately, but the man wasn’t satisfied, and he kicked him again. He took a step back and breathed in a deep breath. “I would kill you now if I thought she wouldn’t be angry with me for it.” He looked back over at Bunny and bent down, scooping her up in his arms. He nuzzled his mouth up to her ear and whispered, “It’s okay sweetheart, nobody can keep us apart now.”<br>
