~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara woke up slowly, dizzy and disoriented. Her vision was a little blurry, and when she tried to lift herself up, it felt like the room was spinning. Once she recognized her surroundings, she forced herself to work past the ill effects to see if her friends were alright. The first person she saw was Nick, who seemed to be waking up as well. She crawled over to him and lightly shook him.<br>
<br>
“Nick, wake up.” He blinked his eyes a few times, trying to focus on her. He narrowed his eyes in temporary confusion.<br>
<br>
“Sara?” She nodded. He started to rise, leaning an elbow on the floor to prop himself up. He looked around the room. “What happened?” She shook her head, immediately regretting the action, and buried her head between her knees to fight the nausea. He grimaced, knowing exactly what she was going through, and put a comforting hand on her back.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know,” she answered, slowly raising her head. “The last thing I remember is talking to Grissom about…” her eyes widened and she frantically looked around for the evidence bag, fearing that it had been taken. She calmed a little when she saw that it hadn’t. Nick nodded, not needing her to complete her sentence.<br>
<br>
“Must have put something in the ventilation system,” Nick concluded, motioning with his head to where the duct was. Sara closed her eyes in thought for a moment.<br>
<br>
“Nick, you don’t think this had anything to do with Bunny do you?” He frowned.<br>
<br>
“Maybe, but security probably got her out of here in time.”<br>
<br>
“Probably?” Her concern furrowed her brow. “We should try to wake up the others.” An officer came stumbling in through the lab door, clutching the wall with his hands to help support him.<br>
<br>
“You alright in here?” He looked at the others lying on the floor. “Don’t worry, everybody’s waking up, just slowly.” Nick nodded, standing up on weak legs.<br>
<br>
“How many rooms have you checked?”<br>
<br>
“Just a few myself, got two other guys on it too though,” the officer offered a small smile. “You want to help or stay here until they wake up?” Nick looked at Sara; her expression was still a little grim.<br>
<br>
“I’ll stay, you should go Nick,” she said, finally standing up, grasping onto the counter for support. He smiled and grabbed her arm lightly to help her.<br>
<br>
“You sure?” She smiled back.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, check the break room first to make sure Bunny made it out okay will you?” He nodded, letting go of her arm.<br>
<br>
“Will do.” Nick and the officer left the lab, and Sara tried to think of a way to wake the others. She was trying to figure out why she had this gnawing feeling in her gut that didn’t have anything to do with the side effects of the knockout gas. She couldn’t shake the feeling that something bad had happened to Bunny, and although it clearly wasn’t her fault, she still felt responsible. Maybe if she had been more insistent that they get her out of Las Vegas sooner, she shook her head. It wouldn’t have done any good, Bunny was as stubborn as she was, and she certainly saw that aspect of her personality. She noticed that Warrick was starting to wake up, and gently crouched down beside him.<br>
<br>
“Hey.” He looked at her and then around the room, as his vision was focusing.<br>
<br>
“Hey.”<br>
<br>
“Nick thinks it was some sort of gas pumped through the vents.” Warrick nodded gently and then rubbed his head.<br>
<br>
“Nice side effects,” he said sarcastically. Sara smiled.<br>
<br>
“It gets better.” She held out her hand to help him up.<br>
<br>
Nick soon appeared in the doorway, with Adrian following him. Sara and Warrick were helping Grissom to a chair. The chemicals in the gas had affected him more than the others, and Sara silently wondered if he should stay at work or go home, though she knew better than to bring up the topic with everything going on. No point in starting a fight when she knew what the outcome would be. Sara looked over at Nick and saw the grim expression on his face.<br>
<br>
“What happened?” He ran his hands through his hair and spoke with a light shake in his voice.<br>
<br>
“I already called an ambulance, it should be here in a couple minutes,” he replied, not really answering Sara’s question. She stepped closer to him, her eyes wider.<br>
<br>
“What happened Nick?” Sara tried her best to keep her voice calm, but it wasn’t easy. Even though they had a picture of the killer now, just working on serial murder cases in addition to their regular workload had put everyone through the ringer. Adrian decided to answer for him when he saw that Nick was just standing there at a loss for words.<br>
<br>
“Bunny’s gone, Ford’s hurt, ambulance is on its way,” he said, getting right to the point. Nick sighed.<br>
<br>
“They’re checking on the security camera tapes right now to see what happened, but if the same guy is responsible…”<br>
<br>
“Then there won’t be anything there,” Grissom finished Nick’s statement for him. Nick nodded. “He certainly seems to be making this personal doesn’t he?” Grissom observed. Sara frowned.<br>
<br>
“Stalkers usually do,” she mumbled in a low voice. Grissom looked up at her thoughtfully, but she quickly covered by motioning to Nick. “Remember when Nick was stalked? That guy made up a whole imaginary friendship in his mind.” Nick winced.<br>
<br>
“She’s right.” Grissom took off his glasses and rubbed his eyes, then put his glasses back on. He shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I get the feeling it’s more than that.” He looked over to Adrian. “Is there any chance that she knew this guy, even if it was just in passing, and just somehow forgot?” Adrian was about to answer when the paramedics came down the hall.<br>
<br>
“I’ll be right back,” he said, indicating one minute with his finger. Sara leaned against the counter and turned her attention back to Grissom.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know, you really think someone as smart as she is would forget knowing someone?”<br>
<br>
“Especially someone who kills people?” Nick added. Grissom shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Anything’s possible children.” Warrick gave a half grin at Grissom’s statement. “She’s smart, but a good memory for some things might not translate to other areas of her life, like for instance, social skills.” He paused, recognizing that statement held true for himself as well, and possibly for Sara. “Let’s go over the scenarios.”<br>
<br>
“Scenario one. Something similar to Nick’s experience. She just briefly met the guy and then he started stalking her,” Warrick said.<br>
<br>
“And Ford put a stop to it, or so he thought, and that’s why he was attacked,” Sara added. Nick shook his head.<br>
<br>
“No. That can’t be it,” Nick said. “Unless he met her before Adrian started working as her bodyguard, then started stalking her a year later.” Sara frowned. Nick was right. The time frame didn’t work, because Adrian would have definitely said something if he had recognized him, even in passing.<br>
<br>
“Okay, scenario two. Maybe he worked for one of her dad’s subsidiary companies. He could have seen her, maybe even met her, and she probably wouldn’t remember him. And Ford wouldn’t necessarily remember him because he doesn’t deal with all the personnel on a daily basis.” She looked at Nick. “And, maybe Adrian wasn’t there, because he’s not with her all the time when she’s at work, just when she leaves the building.” Grissom gave a half grin. Sara frowned and confusion passed over Grissom’s features.<br>
<br>
“Sara?”<br>
<br>
“I was just thinking that couldn’t be completely right either,” she said, starting to pace. “I mean, if that was the case, then why beat up Ford?”<br>
<br>
“No, it still holds Sara. If he knew Ford was the one behind getting him to stop stalking her,” Warrick said. Nick ran a hand over his face, and then crossed his arms, giving a somewhat disgusted look.<br>
<br>
“Or because of something else,” he murmured. Warrick gave him a questioning look and Nick shrugged. “Well, Ford seems to be kind of, um,” he searched for the right word, “attached, to Bunny.” He paused. “Maybe if he met her in passing at one of the company functions or something, Ford was probably there too, and…”<br>
<br>
“And he probably thought that they were involved,” Grissom nodded. “Meaning that the attack may have been motivated by jealousy rather than hatred for him keeping him away from her.” Nick nodded.<br>
<br>
“Yeah.” Sara frowned, furrowing her brow ever so slightly.<br>
<br>
“Why would he think that they were involved?” She had taken his affection for Bunny as concern and protectiveness rather than non-platonic feelings. Grissom cocked an eyebrow at her. “What? Just because he’s been kind of protective toward her these last couple days doesn’t mean that he’s always like that, he has good reason to try and be comforting toward her right now.” Nick rolled his eyes.<br>
<br>
“You’re just saying that because you like him,” he teased. Grissom frowned and shot Nick a warning look. He held up his hands in mock surrender. “Just kidding.”<br>
<br>
“Well,” Sara said thoughtfully, “if he is like that all the time, that would certainly explain the killer’s animosity toward him.” The paramedics went back through the hall carrying Ford, who hadn’t woken up yet, on a stretcher. Adrian came back into the lab. Sara gave him a questioning look with her eyes.<br>
<br>
“It doesn’t look good right now,” he said in an almost sorrowful tone. He and Ford hadn’t always gotten along, primarily because he knew how Ford felt about Bunny, but he still considered him a friend. “Do you need me here?” Grissom shook his head.<br>
<br>
“No. Have you called Mr. Bouchard yet?” Adrian sighed and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, that wasn’t a fun conversation.” Grissom leaned forward in his seat.<br>
<br>
“This wasn’t your fault. There wasn’t anything you could have done to prevent it. If you want me to talk to him I will.” Adrian shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I should have gotten her out of here sooner. I shouldn’t have waited for additional security.” He paused. “You don’t need to talk to him, he didn’t fire me or anything. Finding Bunny and bringing her back safe is his top priority right now. It should be your top priority too.” He looked at Grissom and Grissom nodded.<br>
<br>
“It is.”<br>
<br>
“Good. You can probably expect him to call in some of his contacts from the federal government to look for her.” Grissom sighed.<br>
<br>
“I figured.” Adrian nodded and scribbled something on a piece of paper.<br>
<br>
“Here’s my cell phone number to keep in contact. I’m going to meet Mr. Bouchard at the hospital right now.” He handed the slip of paper to Grissom and turned to leave the lab. He swung back around. “Please keep me posted if you find out anything, even if it’s small.” Grissom took the piece of paper and nodded.<br>
<br>
“No problem.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Bunny began to regain consciousness slowly. Her head was spinning and she felt like she needed to throw up. As she opened her eyes, and got past the spinning room obstacle, she realized that she didn’t know where she was. She felt too sick to panic though, and instead, rolled over onto her stomach on the bed she was on. ‘Okay, bed. Definitely not in the police building anymore. Hotel?’ She opened her eyes again and looked around the room, whatever she could look at without having to move too much. It didn’t look like her room. It was small, modestly decorated, and had a vase of roses and a tablet of paper on the nightstand. She let out a small groan and then reached for the tablet. It had writing scrawled on it, but her vision was still blurry, and after a severe wave of dizziness engulfed her, she let the tablet drop to the ground and closed her eyes.<br>
<br>
A few hours later, she woke up again, not feeling the side effects of the gas nearly as bad this time. She pushed herself off the bed and gazed at the roses. ‘Humph. Probably a bad effort on Ford’s part to try and make me not feel so bad about being moved to a safe house.’ She remembered the pad of paper and glanced down at the floor. She bent down and picked it up, but didn’t immediately recognize the handwriting.<br>
<br>
My Dearest Bunny,<br>
<br>
Don’t fear, I have not left you. I’m just making arrangements for our departure. I’ll be back soon. They won’t ever be able to keep us apart again.<br>
<br>
Love,<br>
<br>
William<br>
<br>
She cocked an eyebrow. ‘Who the hell is William?’ She shrugged off the foreboding feeling that was building in her gut. ‘Well, I’m not sticking around to find out.’ She made her way to the door, but just as she was reaching for the knob, it opened.<br>
<br>
Bunny recognized the man in the doorway as the man from the picture of the killer. He was good looking, but had the aura of danger and wickedness that surrounded him. She stepped away from him. He gave her a big smile that appeared to be genuine.<br>
<br>
“Sweetheart! I’m so glad you’re up. I was starting to worry.” He quickly closed the gap between them and swept her up into a hug. He pulled away slightly, but still had one arm around her, the other hand sweeping up into her hair. “How are you feeling?” She carefully took in the man’s appearance. He was clean, well groomed, but didn’t seem familiar to her other than from the incident. She furrowed her brow.<br>
<br>
“Do I know you?” ‘Okay, probably not the right thing to ask a serial killer Bunny,’ she berated herself. He grinned and brought her into another tight embrace.<br>
<br>
“I know, it’s been far too long since we’ve seen each other hasn’t it?” She could feel his breath on her ear. He pulled back again. “Don’t worry, I’m going to make up for lost time. We’re together now, and we’ll always be together from now on.”<br>
