<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Brass appeared in the doorway of the lab.<br>
<br>
“Hey Gil!” Grissom’s head shot up and he looked over at Brass. He didn’t move from the spot where he was standing though, which was practically hunched over Sara at the computer.<br>
<br>
“Yeah?” Brass gave him a compensatory smile; he knew how hard this series of cases had been on everyone.<br>
<br>
“We just got a 911 call, can you spare a CSI?” Grissom frowned.<br>
<br>
“What’s the call?” Brass shrugged, obviously not having made the connection between the call and the current case.<br>
<br>
“Hotel manager called, said a woman from one of the rooms dialed the front desk and told her to call the police because she was being held hostage.” Grissom and Sara looked at each other, Sara’s mouth having dropped open. She pushed herself out of her chair quickly and practically ran over to Brass.<br>
<br>
“I’ll go.” He eyed her suspiciously.<br>
<br>
“Just dying to spend some time with me or do you know something I don’t know?” Sara smirked.<br>
<br>
“I’m sure I know lots of things you don’t know,” she kidded. Brass and Grissom rolled their eyes. “But, this call could be about Bunny.” He furrowed his brow.<br>
<br>
“Bouchard? I thought you wrapped that case up already?” Sara glanced over at Grissom, who’s neutral expression allowed her to continue.<br>
<br>
“Right, you’ve been out of town, sorry. The killer, William Feagins, gassed the entire building and took her before security could get her out of the state.” Brass’s happy exterior dropped.<br>
<br>
“Crap.” He started walking down the hallway with Sara. “It would have been nice if someone had told me about this.” Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“They probably had other things on their mind.” Brass frowned.<br>
<br>
“Let me grab another couple officers as back up then.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Feagins was worried. Bunny was still conscious, but she was slowly slipping, her eyes closing for longer periods of time. He debated whether to call an ambulance. He didn’t think her blood loss looked that substantial, but being smaller than he was, it’s not like she had a lot of blood to lose. Plus, he was sure that the drug he had given her earlier wasn’t helping, and could be entirely responsible for her current state of losing consciousness. He shook his head; he would just need to take care of his injury himself. He carried a small first aid kit in his luggage, but he didn’t know if it would have enough to take care of her. He rummaged through his bag until he found it.<br>
<br>
An ace bandage, some gauze, a small pack of band-aids in various sizes, alcohol wipes, hydrogen peroxide, Neosporin. He sighed, and went to get a wet washcloth to clean off her wound. He came back and sat on the bed next to her still restrained arm. He didn’t want to take off the handcuffs, because he knew that she would try to escape, but he couldn’t properly take care of the cuts on her wrist if he didn’t. He got up again and dug through the pocket on another pair of pants, until his hand came out holding the key. He came back over to the bed and noticed that Bunny had closed her eyes again. He looked to her chest to make sure she was still breathing, and breathed a sigh of relief himself when he saw that she was. He unlocked her cuff and delicately placed her arm down on the bed, cringing when he saw how bad it really was. He couldn’t believe he had let this happen to the woman he was in love with. He shook away the thought that he was responsible for this and grabbed the washcloth.<br>
<br>
He had quickly cleaned up the wound as best he could, wrapping the ace bandage around the gauze that he had put around it to keep it stable. She was still out. He began to stroke her face and hair in a loving manner, and then lay down next to her. He wrapped a possessive arm across her torso and closed his eyes, and drifted into a dreamless sleep.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Nick tilted his head at the vehicles arriving in the hotel parking lot.<br>
<br>
“Something’s going on,” he observed. He and Warrick had only just gotten there themselves. They jogged over to where Brass was getting out of his car.<br>
<br>
“What’s up?” Warrick asked. Sara got out of the car and nodded at them after getting her kit.<br>
<br>
“Got a 911 call from the manager, says a woman said she was being held hostage in one of the rooms,” Sara filled them in as they made their way to the hotel’s front desk. Sara guessed the woman standing there was in her mid to late forties. The woman cocked her eyebrow at them.<br>
<br>
“Awful lot of people you brought for what could be a prank phone call,” she said. Sara glared at her, but Brass gave her a small smile that let him know who was in charge.<br>
<br>
“We have every reason to believe it wasn’t a prank phone call ma’am,” he said, the authoritative tone to her voice snapped the sarcasm out of her and she blankly nodded. “Which room?”<br>
<br>
“Twelve. It’s around back.” She turned around and grabbed something, then turned back to Brass. “Take the extra key.” She held it out for him and he took it, giving her a questioning expression. She shrugged. “Don’t want you to have to bust down the door. It’s expensive to replace those.” He nodded and left the office.<br>
<br>
“Room twelve, it’s around back,” he told the officers waiting outside. “Manager gave me the extra key,” he smiled. He looked over to Sara, Nick, and Warrick. “You three stay here.” Sara opened her mouth, about to sprout a protest, but Brass pointed his finger at her. “I mean it. You three aren’t prepared to deal with the guy who’s in there. I don’t want you getting hurt.” Sara sighed loudly in disgust. “Stay!” He motioned to the officers to follow him to the other side of the building. Sara grumbled and put her kit on the hood of the car. Her cell phone rang and she flipped it open.<br>
<br>
“Sidle.”<br>
<br>
“Hey it’s Grissom.” She smiled.<br>
<br>
“Brass is making us wait in the parking lot,” she complained.<br>
<br>
“Us?”<br>
<br>
“Nick and Warrick just got here a little before us.”<br>
<br>
“Ah.” He paused for a moment while remembering what he called her for. “We think we might have a match to who hired Feagins to take pictures of Bunny.” Sara snorted.<br>
<br>
“Ford?” Grissom furrowed his brow. He had been so pleased to figure out why that development hadn’t been sitting well with him, and Sara figured it out in a matter of seconds.<br>
<br>
“Uh, well, yes actually.” Sara’s eyes widened in surprise.<br>
<br>
“Grissom, I was just joking.” She could practically sense him rolling his eyes at her.<br>
<br>
“Well, maybe you’re more perceptive than you give yourself credit for Sara.”<br>
<br>
“Ford’s initials are F.A., not B.A.,” she argued. Grissom grinned.<br>
<br>
“Buford Abernathy.” Sara felt her stomach sink.<br>
<br>
“Any news on how he’s doing?” Despite the fact that Ford was in love with his stepsister, Sara still found his charm endearing, and felt bad that he was so badly injured that he was in the hospital.<br>
<br>
“Latest update I had was that he’s been moved to ICU instead of CCU.” Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“Well, that’s something I guess.” Gunshots rang out through the air and Sara almost dropped her phone. “Gris, I gotta go.” She hung up the phone and the three CSIs ran to the other side of the building to see what was going on. They could see two of the officers on the ground and Nick muttered under his breath.<br>
<br>
“Christ.” Warrick nodded. They were usually used to being at the scene of a crime after it happened, not before and during. Nick glanced at Brass, silently asking for permission to come closer. Brass hung his head and then motioned for them to come over. Almost immediately, Brass had his cell phone out and was calling for an ambulance, though it would end up being the coroner’s van that would take the bodies away.<br>
<br>
“What happened?” Sara looked down at the two officers’ bodies and then back up to Brass. He shook his head.<br>
<br>
“He resisted, reached for a gun, they fired a warning shot, but he got off two shots before Murphy,” he motioned toward one of the officers still standing, “took him down.” Nick gave the man a look to acknowledge his good work. Sara peered into the room and frowned.<br>
<br>
“Did he kill her?” Bunny was still unconscious and lying on the bed, only loosely covered by a sheet. Brass gave a half grin.<br>
<br>
“Don’t know. Haven’t been in there yet,” he responded. Sara nodded and pulled her latex gloves on. She walked over to the bed and felt Bunny’s neck for a pulse. It was there, but not strong. She looked back over to Brass for a minute.<br>
<br>
“She’s alive, but just barely.” Brass let out the breath he had been holding in.<br>
<br>
“Thank God.” He said in a quiet voice. “Ambulance should be here in a couple of minutes,” he stated, looking at his watch. Sara took in the room, more specifically the bed. The handcuffs were still attached to the bed, and Sara could see the blood that had fallen from Bunny’s wrist, as it was all over the bed and floor, and on the cuff. She winced at the site. Although she could see that Feagins had bandaged up Bunny’s wrist, she scoffed. ‘It’s like shooting down a bird and mending its wing.’<br>
<br>
The ambulance sirens blared and soon the parking lot on their side of the building was a fury of lights and noise. The paramedics came into the room and put Bunny on a stretcher. Feagins and the two officers were taken away in body bags. Nick snapped Sara out of her thoughts.<br>
<br>
“What?”<br>
<br>
“I said, just think, if Ford hadn’t hired this guy then none of this would have ever happened.” He paused, thoughtful. “Funny how things work out sometimes, huh?” Sara nodded absently. He was right of course, that had been her theory as well after Grissom told her that Ford had been the one to hire Feagins to take pictures of Bunny. That, in the beginning, he was just doing a job, but he became more and more obsessed with her in the months that followed, and eventually gave in to his own psychosis. And, Ford, who loved her, didn’t know that he had hired someone that would eventually bring his own idiosyncrasies into light. Now, both he and Bunny would be in the hospital, and neither may survive. Sara shook her head and went back to her job, collecting samples from throughout the room.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara visited Bunny when her shift let off. It had been three days since they found her, and although there was still a lot of paperwork left over, they were back in the swing of things with the rest of their caseload. Bunny slowly opened her eyes when Sara came into the room.<br>
<br>
“Hey, how are you doing?” Sara said in a gentle voice. Bunny just nodded.<br>
<br>
“Fine I guess. Any idea how much longer they’re going to keep me here?” Sara smiled and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“As long as they want to I guess.” Bunny gave her a mock scowl and Sara laughed. “You only just woke up yesterday, give it time.” Bunny sighed and became serious.<br>
<br>
“They told me about Ford,” she said quietly. Sara kept the solemn expression on her face, but didn’t say anything. “Do you know if he’s going to be okay?” That question caught Sara off guard. She assumed that when Bunny said they told her about Ford, that she meant about hiring Feagins, but that may have been an incorrect assumption.<br>
<br>
“What did they tell you?” Bunny frowned.<br>
<br>
“That he hired Feagins to take pictures of me, that Feagins went all psycho, that he hurt Ford pretty bad when he took me.” Bunny paused, the end of her sentence quieter than the first part. “Have you heard anything about how he’s doing?” Sara shook her head.<br>
<br>
“I can go ask someone if you’d like,” Sara offered. Bunny nodded.<br>
<br>
“That would be great. Adrian’s getting me some ice chips, so he won’t be able to hassle you about it.” Sara nodded. She got up and went into the hallway, but stopped, feeling nauseous from the emotions that she had to push down. She couldn’t see how Bunny could even think about forgiving Ford; charm can only get you so far. She shook her head, and headed toward the nurses’ station.<br>
<br>
“Excuse me,” she asked a middle-aged woman standing in front of her. “Can you tell me how Ford Abernathy is doing? Last I heard, he was in ICU.” The nurse nodded and checked the computer.<br>
<br>
“It says he’s still there. Are you family?” Sara gave her the best fake smile she could muster.<br>
<br>
“No, but my friend in room 414 is. She wanted to know how her brother was doing.” The nurse didn’t smile, but gave Sara a neutral expression.<br>
<br>
“I’ll tell his doctor to come and talk to her when he can,” she said, turning away from Sara, and taking files to another location. The elevators dinged and Sara looked over to see who was getting out.<br>
<br>
“Grissom?” She asked in surprise. He gave her a half grin.<br>
<br>
“What have I told you about getting too personally involved?” He semi kidded. She shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Bunny wants to know how Ford is doing,” she said in a quiet voice, but Grissom still heard her. He frowned.<br>
<br>
“Does she know about…?” Sara nodded before Grissom could finish the question.<br>
<br>
“I think she still thinks of him as her brother, she still loves him. I don’t know how to help her Grissom,” she admitted, a defeated quality to her voice. Grissom came closer, and reached out to touch her upper arm with his hand.<br>
<br>
“You can’t help everybody Sara. You can only do your best to find out who hurt them and get the evidence needed to put them away.” She stared into his eyes. She knew what he was saying was true, but it didn’t make it any easier. She sighed.<br>
<br>
“I feel like this is my fault, I really believed that Ford loved her,” she said. He pursed his lips.<br>
<br>
“He does. Just not in the way that you thought.” Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“Can’t we ever just have a normal case?” Grissom grinned, and began to lead her to the elevators.<br>
<br>
“Where’s the fun in that?”<br>
<br>
<br>
